Titanic Analysis: What does it take to survive?¶

The story of the Titanic is one that has made its mark in history for the sheer loss of life. The following report analyzes a dataset provided by Kaggle that contains the records of 891 passengers from the doomed journey. The main question that this report tries to answer is if there are attributes that made a person more likely to survive. The three main factors that will be analyzed are: average fare price by gender, passenger class by gender, and whether the passenger was traveling alone by gender.

The figures above shows how many valid entries each column has in this dataset. It appears that 177 age records are missing along with the cabin number of 687 passengers. The aren't enough cabin records to determine if cabin location had an impact on survival. Pclass could be used as a proxy for this. The deck plans of the Titanic show what level each class was situated on. The higher the class, the higher the cabin location.

Given that dataset contains most of the records for age, this report will analyze this variable. A seperate dataset will be created with isolating entries that contain age data. Any other analysis will refer to the original passenger manifest dataset.

In [7]:
#Function converts survival outcome into text string
def survival_string(passenger):
    if passenger['Survived']==0:
        return "Did not Survive"
    else:
        return "Survived"
In [8]:
#Add new column with survival outcome as text string
titanic_df['Survival']=titanic_df.apply(survival_string,axis=1)
In [9]:
#Create family_size column
#The dataset provides two columns for group size SibSp(Sibling/Spouse) and Parch(Parent/child).
#These are combined to determine the size of the passengers group overall.
titanic_df['Family_Size']=titanic_df['SibSp']+titanic_df['Parch']
In [10]:
#This function groups passengers by age group
def age_group(passenger):
    age=passenger['Age']
    if age <18:
        return 'child'
    elif age < 65:
        return 'adult' 
    else:
        return 'senior'
In [11]:
#Create age groups
titanic_df['AgeGroup']=titanic_df.apply(age_group,axis=1)
In [12]:
#This function is used to determine if passenger was alone
def p_loner(passenger):
    group=passenger['Family_Size']
    if group >0:
        return 0
    else:
        return 1
In [13]:
#Add column in data for alone/not alone
titanic_df['Alone']=titanic_df.apply(p_loner,axis=1)
In [14]:
#Create new dataset for passengers with age data
titanic_aged_df = titanic_df[np.isfinite(titanic_df['Age'])]

<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x10ef9c890>

The pairplot above gives an overview of the relationship between any two varibles in the dataset. At a glance, it seems like first and second passengers have a higher rate of survival than those in third. Higher classes pay more for their tickets, which one would expect. There were higher rates of survival for younger individuals and this is most notable for passengers in the third class. It seems like a majority of the passengers were between the ages of twenty and forty years old. It seems like there were lower rates of survival for indivduals who either did not come with a sibling/ spouse(Sibsp) or those without children/ parents(Parch). This will be explored in further detail. This report will look at indivudals who were either alone or not by grouping Sibsp and Parch variables.

Additional Insights¶

In [37]:
#showing the ages of survivors vs the ages of those who perished
ax=sns.violinplot(x='Survival',y='Age',hue='Sex',palette='Set1', split=True,data=titanic_aged_df)

The violin plot above shows the the frequency of survival outcome by age and sex. One could infer that there was a higher rate of survival for passengers younger than 20 years old. There may have been a preference to load children onto lifeboats before others.

In [38]:
sns.lmplot(x='Age', y='Fare',hue= 'Survival',data=titanic_aged_df,fit_reg=True)
Out[38]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x119e5a710>

The plot above shows the relationship between age and fare. The line of best seen on the chart indicates an positive relationship between the two variables. In other words, older passengers were more likely to spend more for their ticket. It seems like the relationship between fare and survival outcome weakens after the age of 50.

In [39]:
ax=sns.violinplot(x='Pclass',y='Survival',hue='Sex',palette='Set1', split=True,data=titanic_df)

The violin chart above reiterates the previous findings that there was a higher rate of survival for passengers in the first and second class. This may have been due to the location of the life boats as opposed to different treatment by social class. Given that the cabins of first and second class passengers were closer to the main deck, it likely played a role in the outcome of their survival.

Conclusion¶

After analyzing the data, there seem to be characteristics that made a passenger more likely to survive. An accompanied female traveling in the first class has the highest chance of survival based on these findings.

Women had higher rates of survival overall compared to men. These findings are in line with the historical accounts of the wreck which state that women and children were a priority.

Passengers traveling in first class had a higher rate of survival across both genders. This does not necessarily mean that there could have been a preferance for higher class individuals. One thing to note about the Titanic is that lower classes were located on lower decks. Given that the glacial impact occured at 11PM, one could argue that many passengers were in their respective quarters. First and second class passengers were closer to the main deck which may have given them an upper hand.

While the findings in this report are suggestive, all conclusions are tentative and the aforementioned correlations are not meant to imply causality. With that said, the data from this voyage contains trends that continues to attract the attention of countless data analytic aficionados.
